    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.22"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">22</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">REFER IN REPLY TO THE FOLLOWING:
                
                    UNITED STATES
                        <lb/>
                    <add>c/o</add> DEPARTMENT OF THE INTERIOR
                        <lb/>
                    OFFICE OF INDIAN AFFAIRS
                        <lb/>
                    WASHINGTON
                
                    ADDRESS ONLY THE
                        <lb/>
                    COMMISSIONER OF INDIAN AFFAIRS</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>February 22, 1931</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson, Missouri.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>My dear Mr. Neihartd<sic>Neihardt</sic>:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I received your book to-day, via Pine Ridge. It is a very beautiful work, and I can not express my appreciation of your gracious act in sending me this copy.</p>
                
                <p>In the same mail I happened, rather curiously, to receive some original sktches<sic>sketches</sic> made by Standing Bear. I plan to exhibit both the book and sketches with the collection of Indian art now on show in the Interior Department building for the benefit of the <hi rend="caps">N. E. A.</hi> conference being held in Washington.</p>
                
                <p>I have shown the book around in the office, and it is meeting with distinct favor. It is beautifully written. I am writing to Black Elk and Stnading<sic>Standing</sic> Bear to congratulate them on their material. The charm and delight of the book, however, remain<del/> distinctly yours. My very heart<add>y</add> congratulations, and most sincere appreciation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours very sincerely,</salute>
                
                    <signed><unclear/></signed>
                
                    <note type="unknown">(Frill Agent)</note>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></opener>     <p>I travel a good deal for the Indian Bureau, and I hope I may have occasion to meet you there next summer. However, I am no lonager<sic>longer</sic> in 6harge<sic>Charge</sic> of PineRidge. Mr. McGregor is the superintendent. You will find him eager to cooperate with you, I am sure. He, also, is a good friend of the Indians.</p>
                    
                    <closer><signed>B.C.</signed></closer>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
